children.subject: Not a pro or anything, but I'm a junior who got offers from 4 of the FAANG + offers from other "unicorns" simply doing Leetcode. I started LC in the middle of July and I had finished ~90 by the time school started. Mostly easies and mediums, some hards. I was done recruiting by mid-October but I had re-done those 90 plus another 60 or so by the time I finished. YMMV, but for me, doing Leetcode got me offers, and it felt good to ace interviews whereas I failed every single interview my sophomore year (every single one! feelsbad).
OP: Thanks! For technical skills, is LC the best way to hone the technical skill? Is there anything else beside LC I can do for that? I know for human interview skills, I can hone them with HKN/UPE.

Facebook, Microsoft, and Google (and some other companies) offer Freshmen/Sophomore specific internships. Look into those as well, along with SWE internships, since they're generally slightly easier to get into.
Thanks! Also, what courses best help prepare for the actual internship (assuming it's SWE)?

I found that CS 162 was pretty helpful, as it taught me how to work with and debug a large codebase. CS 186 and CS 161 were also helpful in getting more project experience, and the concepts do pop up in interviews and on the job (especially if you're interested in backend/security).
61B is the singlemost important course imo, after that you are ready.

I got into FAMG (not Apple and Netflix) after sophomore year, and the most important thing was fluency with leetcode style questions. You can usually develop intuition through 61B and 170, but by no means do you need to have taken these courses to get in.

I've taken 161, 162, 168, 170 and 186 and in my biased POV, the 160 series (and 186) are the best for software work since you're working hands on with a codebase and thinking through software design. The other classes are good to haves, but I don't know if the knowledge would be directly applicable to SWE work. Good luck!
What is the best way to get a FAANG internship at the end of my sophomore year?
+1 on getting references. In large companies, having a reference gives you a huge boost over being a random applicant!

Read cracking the coding interview, practice lots of leet code, do mock interviews (UPE + Career center) and work on people/communication skills to match your technical skills.

Also work on networking. Leetcode will help you pass the interview, but not get it. Make friends with upper classman, ask them to refer you, and attend summer fairs at companies you care about to get the recruiters emails so you can just apply through them directly instead of being one of the thousands of resumes they get. Good luck.

Source: Got FAANG internship sophomore year.
How does one find out about these summer intern recruiting events? Will it be posted somewhere online (eg LinkedIn) or is it through word-of-mouth?

You can sign up for Jumpstart, which is a job networking board dedicated for college students! It's jumpstart.me. There are tons of virtual job search events there. The Career Center also sends out a weekly email with virtual job networking opportunities as well.

You can also try to attend conferences, like GHC if you're female identifying, or hackathons!

The summer events mentioned above are generally invite only. But if you've already managed to establish a relationship with the recruiter (e.g. Apple, Google, Microsoft, and Facebook all have specific recruiters assigned to Berkeley, so career center should be able to give you their contact info), it shouldn't be too challenging to get an invite :) Also +1 to Jumpstart

In addition to everything mentioned above, network aggressively. Find a friend interning at your target companies this summer and get them to submit a referral for you (personally not a fan of the 'ask random person on LinkedIn for a referral' strategy, but that's your call to make). Also, most of these companies would host info events/recruiting events in the summer (usually mid-July) to try to poach interns from other companies, so see if you can get yourself onto the invite list for those events and then keep in touch with those recruiters as the school year starts. (Not sure what form those events will take this year with all the virtual internships, but keep your eyes and ears open.)

All the interviewing prep in the world won't matter if you get lost in a pile of resumes and never get scheduled for an interview in the first place.

history.content:
I'm a sophomore with 3.9+ GPA. I had taken all lower-divs and EECS126 (grade was A-) in past semesters, and am taking 170 and 162 this semester for P/NP. I'm interning at a small-ish sized company at an SWE position this summer. 

I plan to take 188 and 161 - two classes of relatively medium to low workload - next semester, and spend the rest of my time doing leetcode intensively.

I really really want to/need to get into FAANG right after graduation, since they're generous on sponsoring visa (I'm an international student). Based on my current situation, where should I spend my time to maximize my chance at FAANG for junior summer internship and beyond? Apart from leetcode, what else should I do? What are some resources I can look at for that specific goal?

Many thanks, friends!

p.s. is it a good idea to P/NP 170 and 162 by the way? I thought industry won't care about transcript as much so I made the decision. (There's no way back though cuz I'll probably get B's lol)
